Conjoined Twins Separation Leading to the Death of One Twin: An Expanded Ethical 
Analysis of Issues Facing the ICU Team.

Cummings BM(1), Paris JJ(2).

Author information:
(1)1 Pediatric Intensive Care, MGH Pediatrics Ethics Committee, Department of 
Pediatrics, Massachusetts General Hospital, Boston, MA, USA.
(2)2 Department of Theology, Boston College, Chestnut Hill, MA, USA.

A recent case of conjoined twins required multiple hospitalizations in the 
pediatric intensive care unit and led to a difficult situation confronting staff 
regarding the potential separation where surgery would result in the death of 
one twin. The hospital ethics committee was consulted. A systematic approach was 
utilized to examine medical standards, historical precedents, and various 
ethical and legal frameworks. The ethics committee believed that either 
proceeding with or forgoing attempted separation surgery would be ethically 
acceptable. We share our reasoning and lessons learned for others facing this 
situation in the future.

